'''Joseph Ogbonnaya Irukwu''' is a Nigerian insurance executive, lawyer, lecturer and author who has written published works about the insurance industry in Africa. He is also a former president of [[Ohanaeze Ndigbo|Ohaneze Ndigbo]], an ethno-political and social group that represents the interest of [[Igbo people|Igbos]] in the Nigerian polity.

Irukwu was the founding managing director of Nigerian Reinsurance Corporation, in 1989, he founded African Development Insurance Company which was later sold to [[Diamond Bank]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201410150238.html|title=Irukwu - Insurance Penetration to Increase By 25 Percent in 2039|last=Duru|first=Nnamdi|date=October 15, 2014|work=Thisday|access-date=}}</ref>

== Life ==
Irukwu obtained his degree in Law and Insurance from a British university in 1962. Upon returning to [[Nigeria]], he found employment with West African Provincial Insurance Company, a British firm operating out of [[Lagos|Lagos.]] Originally, a legal adviser, he rose within the firm and joined the managerial cadre of the firm's insurance department in 1965.<ref name="vbp">{{Cite magazine|date=1982|title=A Look at the Reinsurance Business|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=7485&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=11284271|magazine=Nigerian Enterprise|language=en|location=Lagos|publisher=VBO International|volume=2|issue=7|pages=27-32}}</ref> In 1970, he was appointed chief executive officer of Unity Life and Fire Insurance Company and it was while working at Unity that his profile began to rise. In 1972, the government appointed him head of the student loans board, a committee with the responsibility to disburse loans to thousands of students.<ref name="vbp" /> In 1977, Irukwu became the pioneer chief executive of Nigerian Reinsurance Corporation, a government owned business established to increase the local share of [[reinsurance]] premium income. Prior to the establishment of the firm, insurance firms in Nigeria, conducted reinsurance transactions with foreign companies. To boost the local insurance market and reduce foreign exchange out-flow, the government founded Nigerian Re. The new firm was given the right of first refusal for any reinsurance transaction to be conducted in Nigeria. One of Irukwu's main challenges was to recruit and train talent in a line of business that was new to Nigeria. The firm engaged foreign institutions in the training of workers and sponsored a training school in Lagos.<ref name="vbp" /> 

=== Academic career ===
In the early 1970s, Irukwu began to conduct lectures in actuarial science at University of Lagos. In addition, he was involved in developing training programs at the West African Insurance Companies Association (WAICA) and at the [[West African Insurance Institute]].<ref name="vbp" />

He published his first book, ''Insurance Law and Practice in Nigeria'' in 1967 and his second book, ''Accident and Motor Insurance in West Africa'' was published in 1974. His third book, ''Insurance Management in Africa'' was published in 1976.<ref name="vbp" /> 

